On March [XXX], 2025 at 11:01 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stopped facing southwest on [XXX] in the left turn lane at the intersection of [XXX] waiting for northeastbound traffic to clear before proceeding to turn left onto [XXX]. While the Waymo AV remained stopped as it yielded to traffic, a pickup truck that was stopped directly behind the Waymo AV moved forward and the front of the pickup truck made contact with the rear of the stationary Waymo AV. An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX] in San Francisco. At that time, a cyclist on an eBike came to a stop in the bike lane to the right of the Zoox vehicle. The cyclist began to proceed before the light turned green and headed straight. After the light turned green, the Zoox vehicle proceeded straight towards [XXX]. While nearly through the intersection, the cyclist abruptly veered left into the path of the Zoox vehicle and accelerated toward the front of the Zoox vehicle in violation of a red crosswalk signal and in violation of the Zoox vehicle's right-of-way. The Zoox vehicle appropriately braked hard in response to the cyclist's maneuver, but contact was unavoidable. The eBike laterally impacted the Zoox vehicle's right front fender and body side, then the cyclist impacted the right front body of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then came to a full stop. The cyclist then rode over to the sidewalk and remained briefly stopped on the sidewalk before getting back on the eBike and riding away. The Zoox vehicle cleared the intersection, then pulled over on [XXX], and shortly after was towed from the scene for inspection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the right front body. The police were not called. No injuries were reported nor apparent with the cyclist.
The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX] in San Francisco. At that time, a cyclist on an eBike came to a stop in the bike lane to the right of the Zoox vehicle. The cyclist began to proceed before the light turned green and headed straight. After the light turned green, the Zoox vehicle proceeded straight towards [XXX]. While nearly through the intersection, the cyclist abruptly veered left into the path of the Zoox vehicle and accelerated toward the front of the Zoox vehicle in violation of a red crosswalk signal and in violation of the Zoox vehicle's right-of-way. The Zoox vehicle appropriately braked hard in response to the cyclist's maneuver, but contact was unavoidable. The eBike laterally impacted the Zoox vehicle's right front fender and body side, then the cyclist impacted the right front body of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then came to a full stop. The cyclist then rode over to the sidewalk and remained briefly stopped on the sidewalk before getting back on the eBike and riding away. The Zoox vehicle cleared the intersection, then pulled over on [XXX], and shortly after was towed from the scene for inspection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the right front body. The police were not called. No injuries were reported nor apparent with the cyclist.

The Mercedes-Benz vehicle was traveling southbound in a parking lot located at [XXX], Santa Clara, CA 95051 when the driver engaged L3 ADS system for a few seconds. At this time, a Chevrolet Camaro parked perpendicular to the right of the vehicle, reversed from their parking spot and made contact with the right middle panel of the Mercedes-Benz.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was traveling in lane 4 on southwest-bound [XXX] in San Francisco. At that time a passenger car (Vehicle 2), traveling in the same direction ahead of the Zoox vehicle in the right adjacent lane (lane 5), was attempting to go around a cyclist, on the right side, in lane 5. The Zoox vehicle operator disengaged, Vehicle 2 then swerved left into lane 4 across the path of the Zoox vehicle and the driver-side quarter panel on Vehicle 2 contacted the passenger-side fender and front door of the Zoox vehicle. Both vehicles proceeded a few feet further and pulled over to exchange information. Vehicle 2 appeared to sustain minor damage and the Zoox vehicle did not sustain any damage. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was stopped for a red traffic light on westbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] in San Francisco. An SUV (Vehicle 2) traveling directly behind the Zoox vehicle failed to come to a stop and rear-ended the stopped Zoox vehicle. The SUV driver reversed, then left the scene without attempting to exchange information. After the collision, the Zoox vehicle remained stopped, then later cleared the intersection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the license plate bracket. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called. The Zoox vehicle camera footage shows the SUV driver was not looking ahead at the roadway before or at the time of contact.

The subject Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driving in the back parking lot of the [XXX] in Santa Clara, CA (parallel to the [XXX]). The Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driven in conventional mode when the driver engaged L3 ADS for a few seconds. The driver then disengaged L3 ADS and continued to drive in conventional mode. The vehicle was manually braked to a stop adjacent to vehicles parked in the parking lot, and perpendicular to a parked Chevrolet Camaro. The driver in the Mercedes-Benz then shifted into Park ("P") via the gearshift lever. While the Mercedes-Benz vehicle was stopped, the Chevrolet Camaro reversed out of its parking space and contacted the Mercedes-Benz vehicle at the right rear door. As a result, the right rear corner of the Chevrolet Camaro and the right rear passenger door of the Mercedes-Benz vehicle sustained minor damage. There were no reported injuries to any of the occupants.

While traveling northbound on[XXX] in Martinez, a car pulled out of a driveway on the right side without right of way and collided with the right side of May's vehicle (t-bone.)
May's vehicle was traveling at approximately 20 MPH in a residential neighborhood, and was approximately 1m left of lane center when a black vehicle exited a driveway on the right from behind a fence, facing the road and May's vehicle. This vehicle did not slow down or stop until entering into the roadway and collided with the May vehicle's right side. AVO attempts to swerve to the left but is unable to avoid a collision. 
The primary factor that led to the collision was the other vehicles action proceeding without the right-of-way into the side of the May vehicle. Upon further inspection, it was determined that we did not predict this collision until it was too late to avoid it even by veering. The velocity of the other vehicle was underestimated and was largely given only yield policies as having the most significant likelihood. There is some room for improvement in our response, which we plan to implement in future software releases, namely, an emergency veer policy must exist that is capable of moving quickly and far enough to possibly avoid the collision, more accurate reporting of velocity for slow-moving agents, estimate acceleration when assessing risk, improvements to predictions of the probability of an agent yielding, and adjusting our risk assessment so that it is heading dependent and more risk would be associated with passing close in front of another vehicle.

On January [XXX], 2025 at 6:07 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle near the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX].

While the Waymo AV and the other passenger vehicle were stopped, an SUV approached from behind at an extreme rate of speed and made contact with the passenger vehicle behind the Waymo AV, which then made contact with the rear bumper of the Waymo AV. According to the San Francisco Police Department, the Waymo AV then began to rotate clockwise and, as it was rotating, the front of the SUV made contact with the passenger side of the Waymo AV. The rear of the Waymo AV then made contact with the rear driver side corner of another passenger car that had just begun to proceed straight on northbound [XXX]. According to the San Francisco Police Department, at least two other vehicles were involved in the crash and one of the occupants of the vehicles involved in the crash and a domestic animal were declared deceased at the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV, the passenger vehicle behind the Waymo AV, and the SUV sustained severe damage. The extent of the damage to the other three vehicles is currently unknown. Waymo received notice that five passengers in four of the vehicles involved sustained injuries of varying severity. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because of a fatality. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On December [XXX], 2024 at 8:28 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, CA was in a collision involving two SUV's, a passenger car, and a pick up truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was stopped in autonomous mode facing south at a red light as the lead vehicle in the second from the right lane when an SUV traveling northbound in an oncoming traffic lane ran the red light.  As the oncoming SUV entered the intersection, it made contact with a passenger car traveling east on [XXX].  The oncoming SUV continued through the intersection and swerved to narrowly miss a pedestrian before making contact with the front of the Waymo AV and the front driver side of a stationary pickup truck to the right of the Waymo AV.  The impact from the oncoming SUV caused the Waymo AV to contact another SUV that was also stationary to the left of the Wayo AV at the red traffic light.  The Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode immediately before the oncoming SUV made contact. The stationary SUV that was contacted sustained damage to the passenger side.  The Waymo test driver was transported to a local hospital for medical treatment.

On December [XXX], 2024 at 4:07 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a pick-up truck on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound in the center lane of [XXX] and slowed down to a stop for a queue of traffic. A pick-up truck traveling in the right most lane and next to the Waymo AV began to change lanes into the center lane, and the driver side of the pickup truck made contact with the front passenger front side of the stationary Waymo AV. After this initial contact, the pick-up truck maneuvered to the front of the Waymo AV, came to a stop directly in front of the Waymo AV, and after a few minutes, the pickup truck reversed, and the rear of the pickup truck made contact with the front of the stationary Waymo AV. The Waymo AV remained stopped in lane due to the initial contact the driver of the pickup truck was in and out of their vehicle until leaving the scene. After approximately 4 minutes, the pick-up truck returned, traveling southbound in the right lane of [XXX], and the driver side of the pickup truck made contact with the passenger side of the still stationary Waymo AV. At the time of each point of impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

The Waymo AV yielded to a bicyclist approaching from behind and to the right, who subsequently made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. The contact with the Waymo AV caused a scratch to the rear trunk panel of the Waymo AV. The bicyclist subsequently passed the Waymo AV on the right and left the scene. The passenger within the Waymo AV was not belted at the time of the collision, having buckled it behind them.
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On November [XXX] at 1:27pm, Car 1 (weride av) - while ADS Engaged -  was making a legal, protected, left turn from [XXX]. Car 1, turning onto [XXX], performed the turn from the second lane from the left and was travelling 11 mph when Car 1 then slowed down while still in the intersection. It is at this time Car 1's safety driver disengaged ADS of Car 1 this put car 1 into manual mode. It is at this time when car 2 (Ford f-150 XLT), traveling at 18 mph, approximately less than 13 feet away from Car 1 and also making a left turn from [XXX] within the same lane as car 1, struck and rear ended car 1 while both cars were still in the intersection.
At the time of impact Car 1 (Weride AV) ADS was not engaged.
Car 1 sustained minor damage to its rear bumper and car 2 sustained minor damage to front bumper. Both parties pulled over to exchange information.
Car 2 did not provide Registration and Insurance for their respective car. Car 2's driver did give us driver's license information but the driver of the vehicle (car 2) at the time of the incident was a different person than that represented on the driver's license presented.
There was no injuries, no property damage and no police were called.

As the Waymo AV approached the double parked car, it slowed for a pedestrian walking north across [XXX] between a queue of stopped vehicles in the eastbound lane, headed towards the westbound lanes. A minivan traveling behind the Waymo AV in the rightmost westbound lane then began merging into the left westbound lane and the front driver side corner of the minivan made contact with the rear passenger side corner of the Waymo AV. The pedestrian then continued crossing in front of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On December [XXX], 2024 at 5:14 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a scooter on [XXX] at [XXX].

A scooterist following behind the Waymo AV began to pass the Waymo AV on the left, and the front of the scooter made contact with the rear driver side of the stationary Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The scooterist immediately left the scene.  The Waymo AV was discovered to have sustained damage from the contact during a subsequent inspection of the vehicle on December 9, 2024.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On November [XXX], 2024 Waymo received notice of an allegation that a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Los Angeles, California may have been in a low-speed collision with a non-motorist (pedestrian) on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
On November [XXX], 2024 at 4:04 AM PT a Waymo AV operating in Los Angeles, California was traveling northwest on [XXX] when it began to slow to yield to a pedestrian crossing the street ahead from right to left. After the pedestrian had crossed the path of the Waymo AV, the Waymo AV began to accelerate slightly then immediately began to slow again as the pedestrian turned around and approached the Waymo AV. As the Waymo AV was slowing, the pedestrian may have made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV. 
At the time of the possible impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The pedestrian later claimed to have a minor injury.  The Waymo AV did not sustain any damage. 
Even though this event may involve intentional contact by the pedestrian and the occurrence of actual contact between the Waymo AV and the pedestrian is not clear, Waymo is reporting this event as a crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user (pedestrian) influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and reportedly sustained a minor injury as a result of the event. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On October [XXX], 2024 at 3:58 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on  [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling south in the left lane on [XXX] and came to a stop in a queue of traffic for the red traffic light at the intersection with [XXX]. As the Waymo AV approached the intersection and came to a stop, a passenger car which was following behind the Waymo AV at a low rate of speed approached the Waymo AV from behind and partially crossed into the right-hand travel lane. The passenger car continued proceeding slowly forward until the front of the passenger car made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. After contact occurred, the passenger car remained in contact with the rear of the Waymo AV, and several bystanders approached the passenger car, attempting to communicate with the driver. Once the traffic light turned green, the Waymo AV proceeded through the intersection and pulled over at the curb on the south side of the intersection to avoid obstructing other traffic. While the Waymo AV proceeded through the intersection, the passenger car continued to roll forward into the intersection, and was stopped by several bystanders. Law enforcement communicated to Waymo that the driver of the passenger car was experiencing a medical emergency and was transported from the scene in an ambulance. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On July [xxx], 2024, at 12:59 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in [XXX], California was involved in an alleged collision with a non-motorist (cyclist) at a parking garage exit on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX].

The Waymo AV remained stationary as the cyclist passed in front of the vehicle, slowed, and appeared to begin to dismount. The cyclist then reached out a hand and made contact with the front passenger side of the stationary Waymo AV, backed the bicycle up slightly, dropped the bicycle, then fell to the ground. 
At the time of the possible impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present. The cyclist received medical attention at the scene and was reportedly transported to a hospital by local emergency services. The Waymo AV did not sustain any damage. 
Even though this event may involve intentional contact by the bicyclist with a stationary Waymo AV and the occurrence of actual impact between the Waymo AV and the cycle is not clear, Waymo is reporting this event as a crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a media report included an allegation of a crash and because a vulnerable road user (cyclist) influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and reportedly was transported to a hospital for medical treatment as a result of the event. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On February [XXX], 2024 at 2:34 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a bicyclist on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] and came to a stop at a 4-way stop sign intersection at [XXX]. When it was the Waymo AVs turn at the intersection, the Waymo AV entered the intersection to proceed straight. At this point, a delivery truck traveling eastbound on [XXX] was already in the middle of the intersection (the delivery truck arrived at its stop sign first and proceeded into the intersection before the Waymo AV). As the Waymo AV passed the rear of the delivery truck, an occluded bicyclist who was traveling behind the delivery truck became visible and was making a sharp left turn onto northbound [XXX], in front of the Waymo AVs path. The cyclist had entered the 4-way stop intersection without stopping or yielding. The Waymo AV detected the bicyclist, applied heavy braking, but was unable to avoid contact with the bicyclist before coming to a full stop. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained minor body damage, and the bicyclist reported minor injuries and damage to their bicycle. The Waymo AV remained stopped in the intersection for approximately one minute, and after the path was clear, resumed driving for a short period of time. The Waymo AV was then returned to the scene by one of Waymos roadside assistance specialists. The Waymo AV did not require towing and was returned to the depot in manual mode.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

A Ghost ADS-equipped car was driving engaged Northbound on [XXX]. As always, there were two safety drivers in the car. Traffic was moving in all four lanes at or near the speed limit. The Ghost vehicle was in the right-middle lane. Another vehicle (the "lead" car) entered into the Ghost car's lane from the right. While there were numerous vehicles ahead of the Ghost car before that vehicle entered the lane, the lead vehicle blocked the view of the lane before it. Throughout the incident, traffic in the other three lanes continued at a steady pace.
When the lead vehicle entered into the lane ahead of the Ghost car, the Ghost car applied the brakes to accommodate the intrusion and then continued to match the speed of the lead car. The lead car suddenly slammed the brakes. The Ghost car followed suit, reducing its speed from 19 mps (42.5 mph) to 4.7 mps (10.5 mph) within the next three seconds. The Ghost car was able to match the rapid speed reduction of the lead car and avoid contact.
The driver following the Ghost car was not able to respond as quickly as the Ghost ADS. When the following driver began to apply the brakes, the car was about five meters behind and was traveling at 6.5 mps. At the point of impact, the Ghost vehicle was traveling at 4.78 mps (10.7 mph), matching the lead car. There were no injuries. The vehicles suffered only cosmetic damage, the drivers exchanged information, and the Ghost safety drivers returned to home base in conventional mode.
